def wrangle_var_func(data):
    data['DATE'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(data['DATE']).year
    data.set_index('DATE',inplace=True)
    return(data)
In [5]:
def wrangle_var_series_func(data):
    data.index = pd.DatetimeIndex(data.index).year
    data = data.groupby(data.index).first()
    return data

use_cols = ["indfmt" , "datafmt", "popsrc", "fic", "consol", "fyear", "cusip", "dlc","dltis","dltt","dltr",
            "lt", "teq", "act", "lct", "ap", "at", "pi", "dp", "oiadp", "xint", "ni", "cogs"]
df_funda = pd.read_csv("funda.csv",usecols=use_cols,low_memory=False)
##Filtering Compustat Dataset
df_funda_1 = df_funda[(df_funda["indfmt"]=="INDL")&
                                 (df_funda["datafmt"]=="STD")&
                                 (df_funda["popsrc"]=="D")&
                                 (df_funda["fic"]=="USA")&
                                 (df_funda["consol"]=="C")&
                                 ( df_funda["at"]-df_funda["lct"] != 0 ) &
                                 ( df_funda['at'] != 0 )&
                                 ( df_funda['teq'] != 0 )&
                                 ( df_funda['oiadp'] != 0 )]



#Applying transformations to some columns
df_funda_1['cusip'] = df_funda_1['cusip'].str[0:6]
df_funda_1['dlc'] = df_funda_1['dlc']*1000000
df_funda_1['dltt'] = df_funda_1['dltt']*1000000
df_funda_1 = df_funda_1.sort_values("fyear").reset_index(drop = True)

df_funda_1['debt_face_value']=df_funda_1['dlc']+0.5*df_funda_1['dltt']
df_funda_1 = df_funda_1.loc[df_funda_1['debt_face_value']!=0] #Filtering out 0 face value of debt from the dataset.

#Computing accounting ratios relevant for predicting bankruptcy.
df_funda_1['NI/AT'] = df_funda_1['ni']/df_funda_1['at'] #Ratio of Net Income to Total Assets.
df_funda_1['LT/AT'] = df_funda_1['lt']/df_funda_1['at'] #Ratio of Total Liabilities to Total Assets.
df_funda_1['NetdebtissuedbyNetassets'] = (df_funda_1['dltis'] - df_funda_1['dltr'])/(df_funda_1['at'] - df_funda_1['lct']) #Ratio of Net debt issued by Net Assets.
df_funda_1['Leverage'] = df_funda_1['at']/df_funda_1['teq'] #Leverage.
df_funda_1['InterestBurden'] = (df_funda_1['oiadp'] - df_funda_1['xint'])/df_funda_1['oiadp'] 

# df_funda_1.set_index(['fyear','cusip'],inplace=True)
df_funda_1 = df_funda_1.loc[:,['cusip','fyear','debt_face_value','NI/AT','LT/AT','NetdebtissuedbyNetassets','Leverage','InterestBurden']]

annret = dsf.groupby(by=['cusip','fyear']).apply(lambda x: np.exp(np.sum(np.log(1+x['ret'])))-1)
annret_1 = annret.groupby('cusip').shift()


mktret = dsf.groupby(by=['cusip','fyear']).apply(lambda x: np.exp(np.sum(np.log(1+x['vwretd'])))-1)
mktret_1 = mktret.groupby('cusip').shift()


exret = dsf.groupby(by=['cusip','fyear']).apply(lambda x: np.exp(np.sum(np.log(1+x['exret'])))-1)
exret_1 = exret.groupby('cusip').shift()


sigmae = dsf.groupby(by=['cusip','fyear'])['ret'].std()*np.sqrt(250)
sigmae_1 = sigmae.groupby('cusip').shift()


mkt_cap = dsf.groupby(by=['cusip','fyear'])['mkt_cap'].first()


dsf_temp = dsf.loc[:,['cusip','Industry','permno']].drop_duplicates()
dsf_temp = dsf_temp.drop_duplicates(subset=['cusip'],keep='first')

Total_MKT_CAP = dsf.groupby(by='date')['mkt_cap'].sum()
dsf['Total_mkt_cap'] = Total_MKT_CAP.loc[pd.Index(dsf['date'])].values
del Total_MKT_CAP
dsf['relative_size'] = np.log(dsf['mkt_cap'])/dsf['Total_mkt_cap']
relative_size = dsf.groupby(by=['cusip','fyear'])['relative_size'].mean()

df1 = pd.concat([annret, sigmae, mktret, exret, mkt_cap, annret_1, sigmae_1, mktret_1, exret_1, relative_size], axis=1).reset_index()
df1.columns = ['cusip', 'fyear', 'annret', 'sigmae', 'exret', 'mk_ret','mkt_cap', 'annret_lag', 'sigmae_lag', 'exret_lag', 'mktret_lag','relative_size']


df1 = df1.merge(df_funda_1,on = ["cusip","fyear"],how = "left")
df1 = df1.merge(dsf_temp, on = 'cusip', how = 'left')
df1 = df1.sort_values("fyear").reset_index(drop  = True)
df1 = df1[~df1.fyear.isin([1962,1963, 2020])]

# Term Spread
termspread = tenyear_yield - oneyear_yield
termspread = termspread.to_frame(name='Spread')
termspread = wrangle_var_series_func(termspread)
# Credit Spread
creditspread = AAA_yield - BAA_yield
creditspread = creditspread.to_frame(name='CreditSpread')
creditspread = wrangle_var_series_func(creditspread)
# Apply function to other series
threemonth_yield = wrangle_var_series_func(threemonth_yield.to_frame(name='ThreeMonthYield'))
GDP_growth = wrangle_var_series_func(GDP_growth.to_frame(name='GDPGrowth'))
PI_growth = wrangle_var_series_func(PI_growth.to_frame(name='PIGrowth'))
ActivityIndex = wrangle_var_series_func(ActivityIndex.to_frame(name='ActivityIndex'))
# Combining all the macro-economic variables for the model
macro_var_df = pd.concat([termspread, creditspread, threemonth_yield, GDP_growth, PI_growth, ActivityIndex], axis=1)
macro_var_df.fillna(0, inplace=True)
macro_var_df.index.name = 'fyear'

df2['bankruptcy_dt'].fillna(0, inplace=True)# 0 indicates no-bankruptcy.
df2['bankruptcy_dt']=df2['bankruptcy_dt'].astype(int)
df2.loc[df2['bankruptcy_dt']!=0,'bankruptcy_dt']=1 #1 indicates bankruptcy.
df2.loc[df2['bankruptcy_dt']!=1,'bankruptcy_dt']=0
# Replace infinities with NaN
df2.replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan, inplace=True)

# Ensure 'cusip' is of a consistent data type
df2['cusip'] = df2['cusip'].astype(str)

for i in df2.columns[7:18]:
    # Group by 'cusip' and calculate mean, then reset index to flatten the DataFrame
    mean_values = df2.groupby('cusip')[i].mean().reset_index()
    mean_values.rename(columns={i: f"{i}_mean"}, inplace=True)

    # Merge the mean values back to df2
    df2 = pd.merge(df2, mean_values, on='cusip', how='left')

    # Replace NaNs in the original column with the mean values
    df2[i].fillna(df2[f"{i}_mean"], inplace=True)
    df2.drop(f"{i}_mean", axis=1, inplace=True)

# Convert 'GDPC1_PC1' to numeric
df2['GDPGrowth'] = pd.to_numeric(df2['GDPGrowth'], errors='coerce')
df2['Industry_labels'] = labelencoder.fit_transform(df2['Industry'])
df2['cusip_labels'] = labelencoder.fit_transform(df2['cusip'])
# Fill numeric columns with the value from the previous row
numeric_cols = ['annret_lag', 'sigmae_lag', 'exret_lag', 'mktret_lag', 'relative_size',
                'debt_face_value', 'NI/AT', 'LT/AT', 'NetdebtissuedbyNetassets', 
                'Leverage', 'InterestBurden', 'Spread', 'CreditSpread', 'GDPGrowth', 
                'PIGrowth', 'ActivityIndex']

for col in numeric_cols:
    df2[col].fillna(method='ffill', inplace=True)

# For categorical columns, fill with the most frequent value or a placeholder
categorical_cols = ['Industry_labels', 'cusip_labels']

for col in categorical_cols:
    # Fill with the mode (most frequent value) of the column
    mode_value = df2[col].mode()[0]
    df2[col].fillna(mode_value, inplace=True)
df2.dropna(inplace=True)

Rationale for Features¶

  • fyear: Captures time-specific effects and economic trends, which can influence default rates. Certain years may be associated with higher economic stress, leading to increased defaults.
  • annret_lag: Reflects the firm's past performance. Poor past returns might signal financial distress, potentially increasing default risk (+).
  • sigmae_lag: Earnings volatility can indicate financial instability. Higher volatility is often associated with increased uncertainty and a higher likelihood of default (+).
  • exret_lag: Excess returns over a benchmark assess risk-adjusted performance. Lower excess returns could indicate higher default probability (+).
  • mktret_lag: Overall market performance contextualizes individual firm risk. Poor market conditions can elevate default risks across the board (+).
  • relative_size: Represents firm size. Smaller firms, often having less financial resilience, might face a higher risk of default (+).
  • debt_face_value: High debt levels can strain financial resources, leading to a greater likelihood of default (+).
  • NI/AT (Net Income/Total Assets): A profitability indicator. Lower ratios may signal financial weakness and an increased risk of default (+).
  • LT/AT (Long-term Debt/Total Assets): High leverage ratios can indicate higher financial risk and an increased likelihood of default (+).
  • NetdebtissuedbyNetassets: Reflects the firm's debt management strategy. Higher values can imply greater financial stress and higher default risk (+).
  • Leverage: Measures the firm's financial leverage. Higher leverage typically indicates higher risk and an increased likelihood of default (+).
  • InterestBurden: The ratio of interest expenses to income. A high burden can impact a firm's ability to meet obligations, raising default risk (+).
  • Spread: The yield spread can be a proxy for credit risk. Wider spreads often reflect higher perceived risk and a higher likelihood of default (+).
  • CreditSpread: Similar to Spread, reflects the risk premium demanded by the market, with larger spreads indicating higher default risk (+).
  • GDPGrowth: Economic growth impacts corporate health. Lower GDP growth may signal broader economic difficulties, potentially leading to increased defaults (+).
  • PIGrowth (Personal Income Growth): A macroeconomic indicator; slower growth can indicate economic stress, possibly correlating with higher default rates (+).
  • ActivityIndex: Economic activity levels can influence corporate health. Lower activity levels might be associated with higher default probabilities (+).
  • Industry_labels: Industry-specific risks and trends can significantly impact default likelihood, with some industries being more prone to defaults than others.
  • cusip_labels: Unique identifiers for securities can be used to track and analyze defaults at a more granular, security-specific level.

In [18]:
def basic_logistic_regression(X_train, y_train, X_test):
    X_train_ros, y_train_ros = RandomOverSampler(random_state=903776295).fit_resample(X_train,y_train)
    logreg = LogisticRegression()
    logreg.fit(X_train_ros,y_train_ros)
    y_pred=logreg.predict(X_test)
    y_proba = logreg.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
    coeffs = list(logreg.coef_)
    return y_pred , y_proba, coeffs

def fit_logistic_compute_metrics(X_test, y_test, y_pred, y_proba, coeffs, name):
    print("Accuracy Score:",metrics.accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred))
    print("Precision:",metrics.precision_score(y_test,y_pred))
    print("Recall:",metrics.recall_score(y_test,y_pred),'\n')
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

    print('\nCoeffecients of every feature:\n')
    for idx, val in enumerate(features):
        print(features[idx], " :", coeffs[0][idx])

    logit_roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred)
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_proba)
    plt.figure()
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='Logistic Regression (area = %0.2f)' % logit_roc_auc)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'r--')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title(name)
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()
    
    temp = y_test
    temp['y_proba'] = y_proba
    temp['proba_qcut'] = pd.qcut(temp['y_proba'],q=10,duplicates='drop')
    print(temp.groupby('proba_qcut')['bankruptcy_dt'].sum().plot(kind='bar',title="Number of defaults vs PD decile: "+name))

def fit_model_compute_metrics(X_test, y_test, y_pred, y_proba, name):
    print("Accuracy Score:",metrics.accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred))
    print("Precision:",metrics.precision_score(y_test,y_pred))
    print("Recall:",metrics.recall_score(y_test,y_pred),'\n')
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
    logit_roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred)
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_proba)
    plt.figure()

    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'r--')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title(name)
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()
    
    temp = y_test
    temp['y_proba'] = y_proba
    temp['proba_qcut'] = pd.qcut(temp['y_proba'],q=10,duplicates='drop')

for i in tqdm(range(1991,2020)):
    X_train = df2[features][df2.fyear < i]
    y_train = df2[['bankruptcy_dt']][df2.fyear < i]
    X_test = df2[features][df2.fyear == i]

def Lasso_implement(X_train, y_train, X_test):
    X_train_ros, y_train_ros = RandomOverSampler(random_state=903776295).fit_resample(X_train,y_train)
    logreg = LogisticRegression(penalty='l1',C=100, solver='liblinear')
    logreg.fit(X_train_ros,y_train_ros)
    y_pred=logreg.predict(X_test)
    y_proba = logreg.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
    coeffs = list(logreg.coef_)
    return y_pred , y_proba, coeffs

def Ridge_implement(X_train, y_train, X_test):

    
    X_train_ros, y_train_ros = RandomOverSampler(random_state=903776295).fit_resample(X_train,y_train)

    
    logreg = LogisticRegression(penalty='l2',C=10, solver='liblinear')
    logreg.fit(X_train_ros,y_train_ros)
    y_pred=logreg.predict(X_test)
    y_proba = logreg.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
    coeffs = list(logreg.coef_)
    return y_pred , y_proba, coeffs

import os
import json
from transformers import pipeline, AutoTokenizer, AutoModelForSequenceClassification
from concurrent.futures import ThreadPoolExecutor
import pandas as pd
from tqdm import tqdm

# Load tokenizer and model for sentiment analysis
tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained("ipuneetrathore/bert-base-cased-finetuned-finBERT")
model = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained("ipuneetrathore/bert-base-cased-finetuned-finBERT")
classifier = pipeline('sentiment-analysis', model=model, tokenizer=tokenizer, framework="pt")

def process_json_file(filepath):
    # Check if file is empty
    if os.stat(filepath).st_size == 0:
        company_id = os.path.basename(filepath).split('_')[0]
        year = os.path.basename(filepath).split('_')[1].split('.')[0]
        return [company_id, year, 0]

    try:
        with open(filepath, 'r') as file:
            data = json.load(file)
    except json.JSONDecodeError:
        # Handling JSON decode error (invalid JSON file)
        company_id = os.path.basename(filepath).split('_')[0]
        year = os.path.basename(filepath).split('_')[1].split('.')[0]
        return [company_id, year, 0]

    company_id = data.get('cik', 'Unknown')
    year = data.get('year', 'Unknown')

    sections_to_include = ['section_1', 'section_1A', 'section_1B', 'section_2', 'section_3', 'section_4', 
                           'section_5', 'section_6', 'section_7', 'section_7A', 'section_8', 'section_9', 
                           'section_9A', 'section_9B', 'section_10', 'section_11', 'section_12', 'section_13', 
                           'section_14', 'section_15']
    text_content = " ".join([data.get(section, '') for section in sections_to_include])

    if not text_content.strip():
        return [company_id, year, 0]

    result = classifier(text_content, truncation=True)
    sentiment_score = sum([res['score'] for res in result]) / len(result) if result else 0
    return [company_id, year, sentiment_score]

# Path to the directory containing the JSON files
directory_path = './10K'

# List all JSON files in the directory
file_paths = [os.path.join(directory_path, file) for file in os.listdir(directory_path) if file.endswith('.json')]

# Use ThreadPoolExecutor to process files in parallel
with ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=64) as executor:
    # Wrapping file_paths with tqdm for progress tracking
    results = list(tqdm(executor.map(process_json_file, file_paths), total=len(file_paths)))

# Create DataFrame
df_sentiment = pd.DataFrame(results, columns=['company_id', 'year', 'sentiment'])
df_sentiment.to_csv("sentiment.csv")

Addig Text Based Features¶

  • Improved Contextual Understanding: Text-based features can provide additional context that numeric data alone may not capture, such as management's outlook or market sentiment. This can enhance the model's ability to predict events like bankruptcies, which are often influenced by qualitative factors.

  • Beneficial for Sentiment Analysis: Text from financial reports or news articles can be analyzed for sentiment, which can be a valuable predictor of a company's financial health. Positive sentiment might indicate good financial health, while negative sentiment could be a warning sign of potential problems.

  • Useful in Identifying Trends and Anomalies: Text analysis can help identify emerging trends or anomalies in a company's reporting or in media coverage that may not be immediately apparent from quantitative data.

  • Conditions for Benefit:

    • Quality and Relevance of Text Data: The added text data should be relevant to the prediction task. For example, management discussion and analysis (MD&A) sections from annual reports are likely to be more relevant for bankruptcy prediction than unrelated news articles.
    • Sophisticated Natural Language Processing (NLP) Techniques: Effective text analysis requires advanced NLP techniques to accurately extract sentiment, themes, and other relevant information from text.
    • Integration with Quantitative Data: The text-based features should complement the existing quantitative data, providing a more holistic view of the company's situation.
    • Avoidance of Overfitting: Care must be taken to ensure that the model doesn't overfit the text data, which can be very high-dimensional and noisy.
    • Timely and Consistent Data Availability: The text data used should be consistently available for all companies in the dataset and timely enough to be relevant for the prediction task.

In summary, adding text-based features to a model predicting company bankruptcies can be highly beneficial under conditions where the text data is relevant, high-quality, and analyzed using appropriate NLP techniques. It can provide a richer, more nuanced view of a company's health and prospects than quantitative data alone.
